{
  "text": "T cells to lymph nodes for activation; MDSC downregulation of CD62L on naive T cells reduces this process. [CITATION_1] The MDSC release of reactive oxygen species and peroxynitrite inhibits CD8 + T cells by catalyzing the nitration of the T-cell receptor, thereby preventing T-cellpeptide-MHC interactions. [CITATION_2] MDSCs also downregulate the T-cell receptor-associated zeta chain [CITATION_3] required for T-cell activation. MDSCs directly induce T regulatory (Treg) cells through the production of IL-10, TGF-\u03b2, or ARG1. [CITATION_4] The Treg cells actively downregulate the activation and expansion of antitumor reactive T [CITATION_5] and NK cells. [CITATION_6] MDSCs polarize T cells toward a type 2 tumor-promoting phenotype by IL-10 production and downregulation of macrophage IL-12. T-cell nonresponsiveness to tumor antigens has been shown to be an early event in tumor progression. [CITATION_7] Although T-cell tolerance in cancer has been shown to be mediated by host antigen-presenting cells (APCs), [CITATION_8] the nature of these APCs has not been clear. Recent evidence suggests that MDSCs may represent a population of APCs responsible for induction of antigen-specific CD8 T-cell tolerance in cancer.",
